00:47:04.500 --> 00:47:09.010
Let me talk about Random
Walk, which is a

00:47:09.010 --> 00:47:16.310
central idea in finance.

00:47:16.310 --> 00:47:28.430
The idea is that, if stock
prices are really efficient,

00:47:28.430 --> 00:47:31.000
then any change from
day to day has to

00:47:31.000 --> 00:47:33.450
be due only to news.

00:47:33.450 --> 00:47:37.300
And news is essentially
unforecastable.

00:47:37.300 --> 00:47:40.760
Therefore, stock prices
have to do a random

00:47:40.760 --> 00:47:42.010
walk through time.

00:47:44.710 --> 00:47:47.490
That means that any future
movement in them is always

00:47:47.490 --> 00:47:48.740
unpredictable.

00:47:51.600 --> 00:47:54.830
The changes are totally
random.

00:47:54.830 --> 00:48:01.700
So, the term Random Walk
is an important term.

00:48:01.700 --> 00:48:05.500
It was coined not by a finance
theorist, but by a

00:48:05.500 --> 00:48:10.700
statistician, Karl Pearson,
writing in the scientific

00:48:10.700 --> 00:48:18.390
journal Nature in 1905.

00:48:18.390 --> 00:48:20.410
Now, he didn't link
it to finance.

00:48:20.410 --> 00:48:25.310
But what he said is, the
movements in some -- well, he

00:48:25.310 --> 00:48:26.780
was thinking theoretically.

00:48:26.780 --> 00:48:30.740
Actually, I believe he used
the example of a drunk.

00:48:30.740 --> 00:48:35.090
Let's take someone who
is so drunk that

00:48:35.090 --> 00:48:37.160
each step is random.

00:48:37.160 --> 00:48:42.230
This person has no direction at
all, staggering randomly.

00:48:42.230 --> 00:48:44.830
So, he starts out
at a lamp pole.

00:48:44.830 --> 00:48:48.120
And what would you predict --
this is what Pearson asked --

00:48:48.120 --> 00:48:51.445
what would you predict is his
position in 10 minutes?

00:48:51.445 --> 00:48:54.340
He happens to be at a
lamp pole right now.

00:48:57.230 --> 00:49:02.000
And what Pearson said is, well,
your best forecast is

00:49:02.000 --> 00:49:04.750
that he's right where
he is now.

00:49:04.750 --> 00:49:06.030
Because you have no bias.

00:49:06.030 --> 00:49:08.070
He could go in any direction,
equally likely.

00:49:08.070 --> 00:49:09.510
So, what's most likely?

00:49:09.510 --> 00:49:12.230
It's that he stays right
where he is.

00:49:12.230 --> 00:49:15.130
And what is the probability
distribution?

00:49:15.130 --> 00:49:18.210
Well, it turns out that the
standard deviation around that

00:49:18.210 --> 00:49:21.480
point goes up with the square
root of n steps.

00:49:21.480 --> 00:49:23.125
Because each step is independent
of the other, so

00:49:23.125 --> 00:49:25.580
the square root rule applies.

00:49:25.580 --> 00:49:28.850
So, if you're asked to forecast
his position after an

00:49:28.850 --> 00:49:32.640
hour -- that's a lot of steps
-- you would say, I predict

00:49:32.640 --> 00:49:35.110
he's right where he is now, but
I now have a big standard

00:49:35.110 --> 00:49:37.470
deviation around it.

00:49:37.470 --> 00:49:41.160
Pearson's article is
a very simple idea.

00:49:41.160 --> 00:49:45.650
Among the readers, apparently,
was Albert Einstein and

00:49:45.650 --> 00:49:48.360
Norbert Wiener, the
mathematician who had invented

00:49:48.360 --> 00:49:50.470
a continuous version
of the Random Walk,

00:49:50.470 --> 00:49:52.790
called the Wiener Process.

00:49:52.790 --> 00:49:55.580
But it got into finance later.

00:49:55.580 --> 00:49:59.460
And in the Efficient Markets
revolution, they started to

00:49:59.460 --> 00:50:10.630
realize that stock prices look
more like more like a Random

00:50:10.630 --> 00:50:13.310
Walk than a Head
and Shoulders.

00:50:13.310 --> 00:50:16.220
You look at these Head and
Shoulders patterns and they're

00:50:16.220 --> 00:50:18.890
hard to find.

00:50:18.890 --> 00:50:23.270
So, what is a Random Walk?

00:50:23.270 --> 00:50:24.260
Let me just define it.

00:50:24.260 --> 00:50:29.700
A Random Walk is where you have
a series x sub t equals x

00:50:29.700 --> 00:50:34.720
sub t minus 1 plus epsilon
sub t, where

00:50:34.720 --> 00:50:37.250
epsilon sub t is noise.

00:50:37.250 --> 00:50:40.440
Just unforecastable
noise: mean 0 and

00:50:40.440 --> 00:50:41.690
some standard deviation.

00:50:44.140 --> 00:50:47.160
Ideally, it would be normally
distributed, so it would have

00:50:47.160 --> 00:50:49.680
a bell-shaped curve, and then
the math would be very easy

00:50:49.680 --> 00:50:50.930
and very simple.

00:50:54.290 --> 00:50:58.620
So, I want I want to contrast
that with an alternative,

00:50:58.620 --> 00:51:01.670
which is called a
''First-Order

00:51:01.670 --> 00:51:03.900
Autoregressive.'' Let me
get my notation here.

00:51:08.010 --> 00:51:12.110
Let's take a process that starts
at 100 -- that's like

00:51:12.110 --> 00:51:17.590
the lamp post. We'll say x
sub t equals -- how am I

00:51:17.590 --> 00:51:18.840
putting this --

00:51:21.340 --> 00:51:29.916
100 plus some number rho --
that's a rho -- times x sub t

00:51:29.916 --> 00:51:36.660
minus 1 minus 100 plus
epsilon sub t.

00:51:36.660 --> 00:51:40.630
So, this is an AR-1.

00:51:40.630 --> 00:51:44.570
That's First-Order
Autoregressive.

00:51:44.570 --> 00:51:51.947
It's like a regression model
where 100 times 1 minus rho is

00:51:51.947 --> 00:51:53.110
the constant term.

00:51:53.110 --> 00:51:58.110
And the coefficient of
the lagged x is rho.

00:51:58.110 --> 00:52:07.770
And we usually require that rho
is between minus 1 and 1.

00:52:07.770 --> 00:52:09.940
Normally, rho is positive.

00:52:09.940 --> 00:52:18.640
So, that means that it's
mean-reverting, but slowly.

00:52:21.580 --> 00:52:26.160
First of all, in a special case
where rho equals 1, I

00:52:26.160 --> 00:52:29.755
wouldn't call it an AR-1
anymore, because it reduces to

00:52:29.755 --> 00:52:30.750
a Random Walk, right?

00:52:30.750 --> 00:52:35.080
If you make rho 1, then the
constant term drops out.

00:52:35.080 --> 00:52:38.270
I've got 100 minus 100 --

00:52:38.270 --> 00:52:41.810
there's no constant term --
and then I've got x sub t

00:52:41.810 --> 00:52:44.020
equals x sub t minus 1
plus epsilon sub t,

00:52:44.020 --> 00:52:46.230
that's a Random Walk.

00:52:46.230 --> 00:52:50.870
So, in the extreme case where
rho gets to one, then a

00:52:50.870 --> 00:52:56.560
First-Order Autoregressive
process

00:52:56.560 --> 00:52:59.350
converges to a Random Walk.

