01:02:30.570 --> 01:02:34.000
And then the next time, it'll
only be half, again, as much

01:02:34.000 --> 01:02:37.200
above 100 as it was
the last time.

01:02:37.200 --> 01:02:40.390
So, it tends to go
back to a trend.

01:02:40.390 --> 01:02:44.700
But what I've shown here is
a simulation with a random

01:02:44.700 --> 01:02:52.800
number generator of an AR-1
around a trend, where the

01:02:52.800 --> 01:02:55.245
trend matches the actual trend
in the stock market.

01:02:58.320 --> 01:03:02.070
Now, in this case, this
is not Random Walk.

01:03:02.070 --> 01:03:05.660
And there is a profit
opportunity, and the profit

01:03:05.660 --> 01:03:09.350
opportunity is when it's below
trend, buy, when it's above

01:03:09.350 --> 01:03:10.760
trend, sell.

01:03:10.760 --> 01:03:12.550
Because it will tend to
come back to trend.

01:03:15.190 --> 01:03:19.165
I chose a rho which was very
small, something like 1/2, so

01:03:19.165 --> 01:03:22.460
it tends to come rapidly
back to trend.

01:03:22.460 --> 01:03:24.830
This does look different than
the actual stock market,

01:03:24.830 --> 01:03:26.570
doesn't it?

01:03:26.570 --> 01:03:29.890
You see how much it
hugs the trend?

01:03:29.890 --> 01:03:33.630
So, it doesn't seem
to fit as well.

01:03:33.630 --> 01:03:35.610
I can do simulations
of this, too.

01:03:38.940 --> 01:03:41.760
This is different.

01:03:41.760 --> 01:03:43.380
You can see the difference,
right?

01:03:43.380 --> 01:03:47.650
This pink line doesn't look as
much like the actual stock

01:03:47.650 --> 01:03:52.620
market, because it really
wants this trend.

01:03:52.620 --> 01:03:55.220
We saw trendy ones occasionally,
by chance with a

01:03:55.220 --> 01:03:59.900
Random Walk, but here we're
seeing it's always on a trend.

01:03:59.900 --> 01:04:05.880
And so, in this world, if the
stock market were an AR-1,

01:04:05.880 --> 01:04:07.440
there would be a profitable
strategy.

01:04:07.440 --> 01:04:10.090
Always buy when it's below
trend, and sell when it's

01:04:10.090 --> 01:04:10.990
above trend.

01:04:10.990 --> 01:04:13.260
Because you know it'll come
back, you see how reliable

01:04:13.260 --> 01:04:15.362
this comes back to a trend?

01:04:19.310 --> 01:04:21.430
So, you can see that there's a
fundamental difference, the

01:04:21.430 --> 01:04:27.310
Random Walk seems to fit the
data better than the AR-1.

01:04:27.310 --> 01:04:30.540
The Random Walk theory says
that stock prices

01:04:30.540 --> 01:04:33.630
are not mean reverting.

01:04:33.630 --> 01:04:36.590
Where they go from today
is all random.

01:04:36.590 --> 01:04:39.070
If they're above the historical
trend, it's

01:04:39.070 --> 01:04:39.960
meaningless.

01:04:39.960 --> 01:04:41.970
The historical trend
is just nonsense.

01:04:41.970 --> 01:04:43.230
It's just random.

01:04:43.230 --> 01:04:46.450
And forget trends,
forget anything.

01:04:46.450 --> 01:04:49.020
It's always the drunk at the
lamp post, no matter where you

01:04:49.020 --> 01:04:51.410
are in history.

01:04:51.410 --> 01:04:54.970
This one, if rho is
substantially less than 1, it

01:04:54.970 --> 01:04:57.920
looks a lot different
doesn't it?

01:04:57.920 --> 01:05:01.550
With rho equals 1/2, this is
not the world we live in.

01:05:01.550 --> 01:05:03.690
It would be too easy
to make money.

01:05:03.690 --> 01:05:06.420
All these little oscillations
around the trend I could

01:05:06.420 --> 01:05:07.410
profit from.

01:05:07.410 --> 01:05:09.810
But in the real world,
it's not like that.

01:05:09.810 --> 01:05:19.000
But suppose the real world is
AR-1 with rho equal to 0.99.

01:05:19.000 --> 01:05:21.070
What about that?

01:05:21.070 --> 01:05:24.070
Well that's not much different
from a Random Walk, is it?

01:05:24.070 --> 01:05:25.720
It's going to be hard to
tell the difference.

01:05:29.340 --> 01:05:33.050
In the Efficient Markets Theory
period, people were

01:05:33.050 --> 01:05:36.100
really excited about the
Random Walk Hypothesis.

01:05:36.100 --> 01:05:40.156
That's why Burton Malkiel's
book, A Random Walk Down Wall

01:05:40.156 --> 01:05:41.750
Street, which he came
out with --

01:05:41.750 --> 01:05:44.870
I think it was in 1973,
right after Fama.

01:05:44.870 --> 01:05:50.120
It became a huge best seller, it
sold over a million copies,

01:05:50.120 --> 01:05:53.810
because at that time people
were thinking, this is

01:05:53.810 --> 01:05:56.160
exciting new wisdom.

01:05:56.160 --> 01:05:59.130
We've learned that the stock
market is a Random Walk.

01:05:59.130 --> 01:06:01.790
And there's all kinds of
implications for that.

01:06:01.790 --> 01:06:02.860
The problem is --

01:06:02.860 --> 01:06:05.170
I have to wrap up --

01:06:05.170 --> 01:06:07.790
that the Random Walk Hypothesis

01:06:07.790 --> 01:06:10.340
wasn't exactly right.

01:06:10.340 --> 01:06:13.380
It's sort of right, you've
gotten some insights.

01:06:13.380 --> 01:06:16.840
But you know, maybe the real
world is AR-1 with a

01:06:16.840 --> 01:06:18.750
rho close to 1.

01:06:18.750 --> 01:06:22.590
And in that world, there are
profit opportunities, but they

01:06:22.590 --> 01:06:24.760
take a long time to come.

01:06:24.760 --> 01:06:29.050
So, if the real world is AR-1
with rho equal to 0.99 or

01:06:29.050 --> 01:06:34.570
0.98, that means you
can buy stocks when

01:06:34.570 --> 01:06:35.950
they're below trend.

01:06:35.950 --> 01:06:38.680
But then you have to wait
10, 20 years for them

01:06:38.680 --> 01:06:40.140
to get back to trend.

01:06:40.140 --> 01:06:44.350
So, it's like the drunk
on the lamp pole.

01:06:44.350 --> 01:06:47.580
The drunk is standing next
to a lamp pole, it

01:06:47.580 --> 01:06:48.530
was a random walk.

01:06:48.530 --> 01:06:51.520
But now we put in elastic band
around the drunk's ankle and

01:06:51.520 --> 01:06:55.190
tie it to the lamp pole
and it pulls him back.

01:06:55.190 --> 01:06:58.440
Now, if we have a very loose
elastic, this guy can wander

01:06:58.440 --> 01:07:01.980
for a long time, but will
eventually be pulled back.

01:07:01.980 --> 01:07:04.440
You'd never know when.

01:07:04.440 --> 01:07:08.590
But if you have a tight elastic,
then it would be

01:07:08.590 --> 01:07:11.170
obvious that the drunk
is coming back.

01:07:11.170 --> 01:07:14.430
The problem is that the real
world seems, maybe, to be more

01:07:14.430 --> 01:07:16.900
like the drunk with
the loose elastic.

01:07:16.900 --> 01:07:18.590
And so, it's kind
of unsatisfying.

01:07:18.590 --> 01:07:23.610
You can beat the market, but
simple trading rules like

01:07:23.610 --> 01:07:28.810
Edwards and McGee are not
powerful, short-run profit

01:07:28.810 --> 01:07:29.610
opportunities.

01:07:29.610 --> 01:07:32.630
In that sense, the Efficient
Markets Hypothesis is right.

01:07:32.630 --> 01:07:34.800
So, don't forget the Efficient
Markets Hypothesis.

01:07:34.800 --> 01:07:37.130
I'll repeat what I said
at the beginning.

01:07:37.130 --> 01:07:40.530
It's a half-truth,
it's half true.

01:07:40.530 --> 01:07:43.620
Remember that, but don't put too
much faith in it, either.

